DS28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.wto.org/dol2fe/Pages/FE_Search/FE_S_S009-DP.aspx?language=E&CatalogueIdList=18546,40056,6020,49250&CurrentCatalogueIdIndex=2&FullTextSearch=|title=WT/DS42/2|work=Wto.org|accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref> Japan formally announced to the Dispute Settlement Body that they had accepted the United States' request to join consultations on June 13.\n\n==Results==\nOn February 5, 1997, the United States and Japan notified the Settlement Dispute Body that they had formally settled case DS28. In conclusion, it was agreed that under the [[TRIPS agreement]], WTO members protected the rights of a recording from their country or could request to protect a work for at least fifty years after the end of the calendar year in which the recording was performed or fixed. Japan agreed to modify their [[copyright laws]] to fit these new parameters, effective March 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.wto.org/dol2fe/Pages/FE_Search/FE_S_S009-DP.aspx?language=E&CatalogueIdList=20455,8351,6326,18448&CurrentCatalogueIdIndex=0&FullTextSearch=|title=IP/D/1/Add.1 ; WT/DS28/4|work=Wto.org|accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref> [[Charlene Barshefsky]], the [[United States Trade Representative]] who negotiated the consultations, described the  outcome as a victory for the protection and profitability of iconic American music: \"We sought -- and will now obtain -- protection for U.S. sound recordings from one of the most vibrant and popular periods in the history of American music -- from the swing music of Duke Ellington, the bebop jazz of John Coltrane, the rock and roll of Elvis Presley, Chuck Berry, Little Richard, Johnny Cash, Patsy Cline and the Sixties sounds of Bob Dylan, the Beach Boys and Otis Redding. The remarkable range and stature of the music produced in that quarter-century makes it an important part of our heritage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tcc.export.gov/Trade_Agreements/All_Trade_Agreements/exp_005579.asp|title=TAC Program - Making Trade Agreements Work for You!|work=Export.gov|accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, on June 4, 1997, the European Community ended the dispute settlement proceedings for case DS42 after concluding the revisions made in response to DS28 had sufficiently solved the issues of protecting existing, copyrighted sound recordings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.wto.org/dol2fe/Pages/FE_Search/FE_S_S009-DP.aspx?language=E&CatalogueIdList=18546,40056,6020,49250&CurrentCatalogueIdIndex=0&FullTextSearch=|title=IP/D/4/Add.1 ; WT/DS42/4|work=Wto.org|accessdate=2015-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of WTO dispute settlement cases]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:World Trade Organization dispute settlement cases]]\n[[Category:European Economic Community]]\n[[Category:Japan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Japanese copyright law]]\n[[Category:1990s in Japan]]\n[[Category:1990s in Japanese music]]\n[[Category:Foreign trade of Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Me, Myself, and I are Here", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_Sound_Recording_Trade_Disputes"}
